		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Vndè oportet, illos etiam Tres habere ad vnguem: additis necessariò addendis.
						Sic qui maximè dudum excellebat, Bacon Cancellarius; non multa, sed multu[m].						
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Francis Bacon"/>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="90" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Sic
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="90" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						adhùc
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="90" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ca[e]cilius
						Thesaurarius.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Robert Cecil"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="90" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Sensi sa[e]piùs.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Whence even they ought to memorize these three by heart; while adding those things which must be added necessarily.
				Thus he, who most excelled little while ago, was Lord Chancellor Bacon; not in quantity, but in quality. <!-- CG: This seems like an adequate translation for the Latin play on words. --> <!--JG: Yes, I agree-->
				Thus, till then it was Cecil, Lord High Treasurer. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
