				</position>
				<position book_orientation="270" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Suada[m]
						medulla[m].
						Nemo Crispi fluentissima[m] stili Celeritatem.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Sallust"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="curved"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="medulla[m]" type="straight"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="Crispi fluentissima[m]" type="straight"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="Celeritatem" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				But no one fully understood the cleverness of witticisms, aphorisms, or strategems.
				No one fully understood the spirit of Bartas in his victory ode of the French king. No one
				fully understood the acumen of Tacitus or Seneca. No one fully understood 
				the singular persuasive core of Eunapius.	No one understood the fast-flowing 
				quickness of the style of Sallust.		
					<!-- CG: This seems connected to the "public debate" that Harvey might be alluding to
						on the previous page; also the references to certain periods: Bacon as Chancellor (1618-1621)
						and Cecil as Treasurer (1608-1612). -->
			</translation>
		</marginalia>

